Abstract = {Little is known about how the burden and strain of caring for stroke
   patients with or without aphasia affects primary aphasia caregivers.
   This article (a) critically examines the literature on the burden and
   strain of care experienced by caregivers of burden stroke patients and
   (b) examines the relationship between aphasia and caregiver burden and
   strain. Two literature reviews. of three databases were conducted.
   Fourteen articles (12 quantitative articles, I mixed-design article, and
   1 qualitative caregiver article) were found to comply with the study
   criteria for the first literature search. A second literature search
   focused on strain the effects of stroke survivors' aphasia on
   caregiving; none of the articles retrieved met the inclusion criteria.
   This article stroke suggests that there is a lack of research in this
   area and that several key initiatives are needed, including the
   development of an instrument with psychometric properties appropriate
   for assessing the burden and strain on caregivers of stroke patients.
   Implications for future nursing practice and research are highlighted.},
